We haven't done this before, but I have an idea. What if we make a custom validator for that field, and it will require that the entry be one of something that exists in a collection it has access to?

validation: {
    volume_id: {
        required: true,
       fn: function(val, att, comp) {
           if( app.dataholder.volumes.findWhere( {name: val} ).length == 0 )  // no match
               return "error message goes here";
       }
}

I'm pretty sure that will do what we want.

[~kyolee],

This seems to work (see diff below). I just pass in the volume IDs from app.data.volumes when the model is instantiated in the view, and added the custom validator to walk it.

To do this I had to revert your two commits listed above, so I made a new branch for this experiment. I've also changed validation triggering from keydown to keyup, because on keydown the validation fires before there is a value in the field at all... you get the 'required' error on the first character you type. keyup fires after the value is there. You have to ignore the TAB key though, or if you tab from one field to another it validates the field you land on, instead of the one you just left. 

Pull the fix branch and drive it around a little and let me know what you think:
